surveys.narrative:
Strawberry Lake is a designated stream trout lake that is presently managed for rainbow trout. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles were measured on August 12, 2015 to monitor habitat for trout. Optimal thermal and oxygen conditions for rainbow trout (11-19 C, greater than or equal to 5 ppm DO) occurred in about 2 vertical ft from a depth of 22 ft through 23 ft and the TDO3 value was 15.6 C. This was similar to the habitat found in 2013 and 2014, and a significant improvement over the oxythermal conditions found in August 2012 when the coolest oxygenated water was 25 C, a temperature lethal to trout. Strawberry Lake has never had very good temperature-oxygen conditions for trout in August, but most years from 2007 through 2015 have had conditions sufficient for trout survival during late summer.

Strawberry Lake is normally stocked with about 1200 yearling rainbow trout each spring.

Designated stream trout lakes have additional angling regulations. Be sure to consult the current Minnesota Fishing Regulations book for regulations, seasons, and possession limits before fishing designated trout waters.

F] and greater than or equal to 5 ppm DO) occurred in about in about 6 vertical ft in June, declined to 2 ft in July, and optimal conditions for Rainbow Trout were absent in the August measurement. Oxythermal habitat conditions were poor for trout in August 2020 (TDO3 > 15), similar to the poor trout habitat found most years in late summer.

Strawberry Lake is normally stocked with about 1,200 yearling Rainbow Trout each spring.

Strawberry Lake is a designated stream trout lake. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profile were measured in August 2008 to monitor habitat for trout. On August 28, optimal temperature and oxygen conditions for rainbow trout were not present. Adequate oxygen for trout was found down to about 19 ft at a temperature of 70.3 F.

Strawberry Lake is a 20 acre lake located 6 miles northeast of Pequot Lakes in Crow Wing County. A small gravel public access is located on the eastern shore. Water clarity is good with a secchi disk reading of 17.0'. Strawberry is a designated stream trout lake. Designated stream trout lakes have additional angling regulations. Be sure to consult the current Minnesota Fishing Regulations book for regulations, seasons, and possession limits before fishing designated trout waters.

Rainbow Trout are stocked annual as spring yearlings (1,200/year). The gill net catch of 34.5/net was the highest catch observed on Strawberry. Average length was 11.1".

Largemouth Bass were sampled in high numbers in gill nets (3.5/net) and trap nets (4.0/net) when compared to similar lakes. Most ran on the small side with an average length of 10.7" for gill net captured fish and 9.6" for fish from trap nets. Bluegills were sampled in average numbers at 33.4/trap net. Average length was 6.5" with 34% at least 7" in length. The presence of Largemouth Bass and Bluegills will degrade the quality of the trout angling in Strawberry Lake through competition with the trout and predation on trout.

No invasive species have been found in Strawberry but are in the area. Before and after launching, lake users are required to inspect and remove any aquatic plants and animals from their watercraft and trailers as well as pull the plug and drain all water from the watercraft, including bilges, livewells and baitwells.

Strawberry Lake is a designated stream trout lake that is presently managed for rainbow trout. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles were measured on August 14, 2013 to monitor habitat for trout. Optimal conditions optimal for rainbow trout (11-19 C, > 5 ppm DO) occurred in about 4 vertical ft from a depth of 18 ft through 21 ft and the TDO3 value was 14.2 C. This was a significant improvement over the oxythermal conditions found in August 2012 when the coolest oxygenated water was 25 C, a temperature lethal to trout. Strawberry Lake has never had very good temperature-oxygen conditions for trout in August, but except for 2012 has always had conditions sufficient for trout survival during late summer.

Strawberry Lake is a designated stream trout lake that is presently managed for rainbow trout. The dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles were measured on August 20, 2014 to monitor habitat for trout. Optimal conditions optimal for rainbow trout (11-19 C, greater than or equal to 5 ppm DO) occurred in about 3 vertical ft from a depth of 20 ft through 22 ft and the TDO3 value was 14.9 C. This was similar to the habitat found in 2013, and a significant improvement over the oxythermal conditions found in August 2012 when the coolest oxygenated water was 25 C, a temperature lethal to trout. Strawberry Lake has never had very good temperature-oxygen conditions for trout in August, but except for 2012 has always had conditions sufficient for trout survival during late summer.

Rainbow trout numbers are almost twice as high as the statewide averages. Local medians and quartile are not available. Sixty-seven percent of the trout were represented in age class 2. Very high numbers of white sucker were captured in the gill nets. Young-of-the-year white sucker and yellow bullhead as well as seven species of minnow were sampled in the natural reproduction check.
